/**
 * Function: Test resetting a calculation node with new dependencies
 *
 * @param a First input value
 * @param b Second input value
 * @param c Third input value
 * @return int The result after resetting calculation to use different dependencies
 */
int test_calculation_reset(int a, int b, int c) {
    // 1. Create reactive variables
    reaction::Var<int> varA(a);
    reaction::Var<int> varB(b);
    reaction::Var<int> varC(c);

    // 2. Create initial calculation that depends on a and b
    auto initialCalc = varA + varB;

    // Force evaluation to ensure calculation is active
    int initialResult = initialCalc();

    // 3. Reset calculation with different dependencies (b and c)
    // In the reaction library, calculations are typically reset by creating new expressions
    // The library uses expression templates, so we create a new calculation
    auto resetCalc = varB + varC;

    // 4. Return result after reset
    return resetCalc();
}

}  // namespace test_reaction
```

This implementation:

1. Creates three reactive variables using `reaction::Var<int>` with the input values
2. Creates an initial calculation that adds the first two variables (a + b)
3. "Resets" the calculation by creating a new expression that adds the second and third variables (b + c)
4. Returns the result of the new calculation

The reaction library uses expression templates and reactive variables that automatically track dependencies. When we create a new calculation expression, it establishes new dependency relationships in the reactive graph.

